      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn the previous text (<htcite0>), we observed that multiplication is present when we write or read texts. Because the symbols used in mathematical operations are not explicit, readers often overlook these operations.\n\nWhen we write numbers, all the mathematical operations mentioned in the previous text also appear here, but there are further aspects we wish to explore. And that is what we will do in this text.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d6e1132d-831d-45b6-a510-9009086928e5",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Reading and Multiplying",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_table_10",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiplication Table of 10\n\nWhen we begin studying multiplication, we first use our hands (<htcite0>), and we'll use them again for this multiplication table.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the Same Number",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Left hand</td><td>Right hand</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"imgLH\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgLH', '0%')\" src=\"images/Left_Hand.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img id=\"imgRH\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgRH', '0%')\" src=\"images/Right_Hand.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\">Figure 1: Hands reprsentation. The source codes are available in project GitHub (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('240800f3-ede4-4deb-9d4e-915a3a03fa68'); return false;\">History Tracers Team, <htdate0>, Source code</a>)</td></tr></table></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The figure shows a person's two hands raised with all fingers extended.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Multiplication with Multiple Digits\n\nUsing the definition of multiplication as the sum of equal quantities (<htcite0>), before performing multiplication, let's recall how to add numbers with multiple digits. Hover your mouse over the numbers below:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the Same Number",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class=\"sumexample1\" id=\"cmtc2\">1 </span><span class=\"sumexample1\" id=\"cmtc1\">0 </span> <br />+ </span><span class=\"sumexample1\" id=\"cmbc2\">1 </span><span class=\"sumexample1\" id=\"cmbc1\">0 </span><br />_____<br /></span>&nbsp; <span class=\"sumexample1\" id=\"cmrc2\">2 </span><span class=\"sumexample1\" id=\"cmrc1\">0 </span></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 1: Addition of numbers 10 and 10.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Notice that when adding numbers with multiple digits, we perform the operation step by step, always working from right to left.\n\nNow, let's rewrite **Calculation 1** as a multiplication. Hover your mouse (or touch) the numbers to visualize the operation:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmtc2\">1 </span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmtc1\">0 </span> <br />× &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmbc1\">2 </span><br />_____<br /></span>&nbsp; <span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmrc2\">2 </span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmrc1\">0 </span></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 2: Multiplication of 10 by 2.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In **Calculation 2**, when hovering over the numbers in the top row, we see that each digit is multiplied by the single digit in the second row - exactly as in the previous operation. Let's compare:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"indigenous_period\"><tr><th>Column</th><th>Calculation 1</th><th>Calculation 2</th><th>Result</th></tr> <tr><td>Ones</td><td>0 + 0 </td><td> 0 × 2 </td><td> 0 </td></tr> <tr><td>Tens</td><td>1 + 1 </td><td> 1 × 2 </td><td> 2 </td></tr> </table>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Through these calculations and the table, we again see how multiplication represents repeated addition.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Building the Multiplication Table\n\nTo create the multiplication table for ten (10), we apply **Formula 1**, assigning the value ten (10) to factor **a**:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>r</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>a</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 1: General multiplication table formula.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div id=\"mParent10\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Visualizing the Table\n\nOnce again, we plot the points and connect them in a single chart:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htchart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart1\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 1: Points from the ten times table connected, forming a straight line. Chart generated using the <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htcleansources(); htfillreferencesource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart js</a> library.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "The multiplication **10 × 10 = 100** will be explained in detail in the next section.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
